NAME
       set-network-protocol-security-configuration - sets the security configuration for a protocol

SYNOPSIS
           set-network-protocol-security-configuration [--help]
           [--enabled={false|true}] [--dynamic={false|true}]
           [--tls1-enabled={false|true}] [--tls11-enabled={false|true}]
           [--tls12-enabled={false|true}] [--tls13-enabled={false|true}]
           [--keystore keystore] [--keystore-password password]
           [--truststore trustsore] -[--tuststore-password password]
           [--session-cache-size session-cache-size] [--session-timeout session-timeout]
           [--certificate-nickname cert-name] [--client-auth={need|want|}]
           [--target target]
           protocol-name

DESCRIPTION
       The set-network-protocol-security-configuration subcommand sets the details of the security
       configuration of a given protocol. When multiple TLS versions are allowed, Payara Server will
       attempt to use the most secure available, falling back to a less secure version if the client
       does not support it.

OPTIONS
       --help, -?
           Displays the help text for the subcommand.

       --enabled
           If set to true, the protocol runs SSL/TLS.

       --tls1-enabled
           If set to true, TLS version 1 is allowed to be used when making a connection.

       --tls11-enabled
           If set to true, TLS version 1.1 is allowed to be used when making a connection.

       --tls12-enabled
           If set to true, TLS version 1.2 is allowed to be used when making a connection.

       --tls13-enabled
           If set to true, TLS version 1.3 is allowed to be used when making a connection.

       --keystore
           Name of the keystore file i.e. keystore.jks

       --keystore-password
           Password for the keystore file

       --truststore
           Name of the truststore file i.e cacerts.jks

       --truststore-password
           Password for the truststore file

       --trust-algorithm
           Name of the trust management algorithm (for example, PKIX) to use for certification path validation

       --session-timeout
           How long before TLS session expire from the cache.

       --session-cache-size
           How large the TLS session cache can get

       --certificate-nickname
           Takes a single value, identifies the server's default keypair and certificate.

       --client-auth
           Determines if if the engine will request (want) or require (need) client authentication
           Valid values:  want, need, or left blank

       --target
           Creates the protocol only on the specified target. Valid values are
           as follows:

           server
               Creates the protocol on the default server instance. This is
               the default value.

           configuration-name
               Creates the protocol in the specified configuration.

           cluster-name
               Creates the protocol on all server instances in the specified
               cluster.

           standalone-instance-name
               Creates the protocol on the specified standalone server
               instance.

OPERANDS
       protocol-name
           The name of the protocol.

EXAMPLES
       Example 1, Set security to be enabled with TLS 1.3 only on http-listener-2

               asadmin> set-network-protocol-security-configuration --enabled=true --tls1-enabled=false
                --tls11-enabled false --tls12-enabled false --tls13-enabled true http-listener-2

EXIT STATUS
       0
           command executed successfully

       1
           error in executing the command

